<div class="penelope">
  <img src="/img/welcomingcat.png" alt="Penelope the Neocities cat">
  <div class="penelope-Bubble">
    <p>Those pointy-bracket things are called <strong>tags</strong>, and they're the whole trick to HTML. Once you can write a tag, you can build anything.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<p>The language web pages are written in is called <strong>HTML</strong>. It's ordinary text, plus tags that tell the browser what each piece of the page <em>is</em>: a paragraph, a heading, a picture, a link.</p>

<p>Most tags come in pairs that wrap around content, like bookends:</p>

<div class="tag-Anatomy" aria-label="The anatomy of an HTML element">
  <span class="tag-Part"><code class="anatomy-Tag"><%= '<p>' %></code><small>opening tag</small></span>
  <span class="tag-Part"><span class="tag-Content">Hello there!</span><small>your content</small></span>
  <span class="tag-Part"><code class="anatomy-Tag"><%= '</p>' %></code><small>closing tag</small></span>
</div>

<p>The whole package &mdash; opening tag, content, closing tag &mdash; is called an <strong>element</strong>. This one is a <code>p</code> element, <em>p</em> for <strong>paragraph</strong>. The closing tag looks just like the opening tag, but with a slash: <code><%= '</p>' %></code>. That slash is how the browser knows the paragraph is over.</p>

<div class="your-Turn">
  <h4><i class="fa fa-pencil" aria-hidden="true"></i> Your turn</h4>
  <ol>
    <li>Turn your greeting into a proper paragraph: type <code><%= '<p>' %></code> right before it and <code><%= '</p>' %></code> right after it.</li>
    <li>Then add a <strong>second paragraph</strong> on a new line below &mdash; a sentence about you, or what you want this site to be. Something like: <code><%= '<p>I am learning HTML, and I built this page myself.</p>' %></code></li>
    <li>Click <strong>Check My Work</strong>.</li>
  </ol>
</div>

<div class="bonus-Box">
  <h4>Why do we even need tags?</h4>
  <p>Try pressing Enter a bunch of times between two words in the editor &mdash; the preview ignores it! Browsers squish all blank space together. Tags like <code><%= '<p>' %></code> are how you tell the browser where things actually begin and end.</p>
</div>

<script>
  function lessonCheck(doc, html) {
    var paragraphs = doc.querySelectorAll('body p')

    if(paragraphs.length == 0)
      return {ok: false, message: 'I don&rsquo;t see a ' + codeSample('<p>') + ' tag yet. Type ' + codeSample('<p>') + ' before your greeting and ' + codeSample('</p>') + ' after it.'}

    if(missingClosingTag(html, 'p'))
      return {ok: false, message: 'A paragraph is missing its closing tag. Every ' + codeSample('<p>') + ' needs a matching ' + codeSample('</p>') + ' &mdash; don&rsquo;t forget the slash!'}

    var withText = 0
    for(var i = 0; i < paragraphs.length; i++) {
      if(paragraphs[i].textContent.trim() != '')
        withText++
    }

    if(withText == 0)
      return {ok: false, message: 'Your paragraph tags are there, but they&rsquo;re empty! Put some words between ' + codeSample('<p>') + ' and ' + codeSample('</p>') + '.'}

    if(withText == 1)
      return {ok: false, message: 'One paragraph down! Now add a second ' + codeSample('<p>') + ' below it with a sentence about you or your site.'}

    return {ok: true, message: 'Two proper paragraph elements &mdash; you&rsquo;re writing HTML!'}
  }
</script>
